content: I want to like it, but this game is like Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde. The normal and Nightmare modes are so easy that in at least 20 of the 30 levels I've played, the enemies never make it past the first set of towers along their path. Nightmare mode is not much harder. No challenge at all. But then comes Hell mode. R-I-D-I-C-U-L-O-U-S! By the 5th level, the enemies come out and the range ones shoot so fast that even with 1000+ HP, your heroes will lose all their health in seconds, before you can move all three out of harms way. And without your heroes, forget it. Even ignoring trying to get 3 stars by sticking to the hilarious "No barracks" criteria, it is completely impossible. And you can't upgrade towers after completing regular level 20 without the stars from Hell mode, but there is no way to GET any stars from Hell move without maybe upgrading towers more.  Too easy and then too hard. And not one single level that is in the sweet spot where it is fun to play. You're either bored, or infuriated. I gave it a 2nd star only because I honestly don't think buying upgrades would help with Hell mode. So at least it isn't a Pay to Win game. But it needs a lot of work to balance it out.

content: Reminds me of a mix of league for tower defense.

Looks like kingdom rush, plays nothing like kingdom rush. The towers in this game barely do anything, it's all about the heroes. That's the first part I don't like about this "TD". Second part: It's a grind game. You need to level up your heroes or buy lots of power-ups to beat the highest difficulty. It doesn't feel like a strategy game. Third part that sucks: learning/power curve. First 19 levels are extremely easy. I wouldn't be surprised if you could complete them without building any towers, just using heroes. 20-27 (that's as far as I felt like playing before deinstalling) are much, much harder, but ultimately feel like a good challenge, though I can see some players giving up around those levels. Then there's nightmare. Often you can only build one type of tower (there goes your strategy) and they're just impossible (map 6+) without playing a few hours to level your heroes or buying better gear. The final complaint: You can compete with other players on a certain map. Highest player in the group gets rewards etc. Great idea, except for one thing: all the highest players use one or two heroes that are unavailable using in-game currencies, making it pay-to-win. I don't mind supporting the developer by buying something, but the prices are high and the rewards little. TL;DR: Just play kingdom rush instead.

content: This is a fantastically designed tower defense game with a wonderfully integrated mobile hero combat strategy element that separates it from other games in the genre. Heroes and towers have upgradeable abilities adding an rpg element to gameplay as well. Easy pick up and play mechanics for anyone familiar with the TD platform, and many levels and 3 difficulty settings for high replayability. Reminds me of the classic Kingdom Rush series created by TD pioneers Ironhide, but manages to put a refreshing new spin on an old classic style of gameplay. Very well made game, highly recommended for any TD enthusiast as well as those just entering the genre.

content: I love it! im here waiting for more update... good luck for the improvement

This game is actually very fun to play. It takes a lot of elements from the 
game Kingdom Rush (it was obviously inspired by) that I enjoyed. Swarms of 
enemies falling to my towers and heroes is very satisfying. It is not very 
strategic like Kingdom Rush is and levels can get boring because the same 
strategy usually works every level (minus any levels with fliers). The 
biggest problem with the game is the greed of the developers. This may not 
come as a surprise from a company doing the bare minimum of keeping their 
game from being a clone of an already successful game (I personally think 
it's different enough from Kingdom Rush to be unique), but they use every 
tactic short of loot boxes and energy bars to get you to spend money. 
Instead of having reusable skills, you have to earn or buy more. Heroes 
take forever to level so use gems to speed up the process. Some heroes are 
behind a paywall, you can't get everyone with in-game currency, and these 
heroes are basically so good you can call this pay to win. The worst 
offender is the VIP status. You can't even buy some things without having 
first bought enough gems, heroes, etc. to raise your VIP level. Plus the 
VIP levels give you more in-game currency and tournament tries per day, 
making it more pay to win. If I wanna get a character in a bundle and 
support you with my hard earned money, don't tell me I can't do so unless I 
buy something else first, you morons. Let me give you my money! Bad 
business practices. This is unforgivable, but most of the game is playable 
without giving a cent and it is very fun, as mentioned before. So it gets 
probably more stars than it deserves with a 3.
replyContent: Hi Harrison Mercer, the money system is very fair. You can get most through in-game grind. All runes, all upgrades can be earned through in-game actions. The tournament is all of free heroes. The top players are using free heroes, too. Thank you

Comparable with my review of the free version: The premium version of 
Empire Warriors TD came as a generous & appreciated alternate, as I got it 
during a cost-free special offer phase. We get VIP1 status for free, Miria 
the mage & arcane artillery in one heroine, and do not worry - the ads 
remained, LOL!!! The game did remind me and others of kingdom rush series, 
but actually this supposed copycat DOES go its own way. While I still think 
imbalance remains an issue the attitude of the developers seems very player 
friendly, and much less greedy than others. Though perhaps a little bit 
less ads, OK, that Sith Raid AD about Star Wars Galaxy of Heroes was 
actually beeping cool! The game runs very stable (no crashes on chromebook 
R13), touchpad & touchscreen both work decently well (until we meddled with 
the config due chrome://flags), and the generosity of the devs allows us to 
bridge 2 crucial spots where heroes (more than one) must take down waves of 
enemy flyers. I did not yet replay that far, but I fear the robed bad guy 
outside the dwarven fort (gates to reach the dwarves) will still kill my 
maxed angel, slay my heroes & heroines, and reach victory with around 50% 
HP... All towers were maxed, all upgrades applied on infantry, mages, 
archers... Still: Thank you for a very improved game version which even 
runs during throttled connection times, that is a really appreciated 
achievement, as it means foreign countries with less Inet can still play as 
equals!
